  "preFix": {
    "title": "Woven wall hanging with a shaped outline",
    "subtitle": "This tapestry panel has scalloped or stepped edges woven to shape",
    "excerpt": "A 30 cm x 40 cm tapestry panel where the outer edge is woven to a shaped profile rather than a straight horizontal line. The shape is built up by weaving short rows that progressively reduce or extend the woven area, then finishing the shaped edge with knots or wrapping.",
    "sourceNotes": "- Shaped tapestry weaving using stepped-weft technique is a standard technique documented across many public domain and contemporary fibre arts references. No specific source quotation used.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Most tapestry panels have a straight horizontal top and bottom edge. This project introduces shaped-edge weaving: the lower edge of the panel is stepped, scalloped, or arched rather than straight, by using ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "short rows",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmpstfodo0000w8v4w8h94bzo"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " at the outer edges of the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "warp",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmpb8pr5y0000zcv47rbtixb7"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ". The finished panel hangs as a 30 cm x 40 cm rectangular piece at the top but tapers or curves at the lower outline.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "suppliesCard",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              "Tapestry loom, minimum 35 cm wide",
              "Cotton or linen warp thread, 1-2 mm, approximately 50 m",
              "Tapestry weft yarns in your chosen palette (wool tapestry yarn, 3-5 colours)",
              "Tapestry bobbins, one per colour",
              "Tapestry beater or comb",
              "Shed stick",
              "Scissors",
              "Tape measure",
              "Paper for the cartoon",
              "Marker pen for tracing onto warp"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "weavingDraft",
          "attrs": {
            "definition": {
              "tieUp": [
                [
                  1,
                  0
                ],
                [
                  0,
                  1
                ]
              ],
              "title": "Tapestry plain weave: single-heddle shed setup",
              "loomType": "rigid-heddle",
              "threading": [
                1,
                2,
                1,
                2,
                1,
                2,
                1,
                2
              ],
              "treadling": [
                1,
                2,
                1,
                2
              ]
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "The draft above shows the plain weave structure used throughout. All patterning in this piece comes from colour changes and short-row shaping, not from a complex tie-up.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Planning the shaped edge on the cartoon",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 1: Cut paper to exactly 30 cm x 40 cm. This is your full-scale ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "cartoon",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpd4m5wk00016wv4vfrtogqy"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": ".",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 2: Draw the shaped lower edge on the cartoon. A simple first option: three rounded scallops across the 30 cm width, each scallop approximately 10 cm wide and 5-8 cm deep at its lowest point.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 3: Mark horizontal lines at every 2 cm on the cartoon. These mark the approximate weft-row positions and help you plan where each short row must stop to build the curve.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 4: Attach the cartoon behind the warped loom. Trace the shaped lower edge outline onto the ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "warp",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpb8pr5y0000zcv47rbtixb7"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " threads with a waterproof marker, visible from the front.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Warping and threading",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 1: Warp the loom at 6 ends per 5 cm (approximately 8 EPI) for tapestry. At 30 cm, this is approximately 48-50 warp ends. Space them evenly across the top bar.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 2: Leave at least 15 cm of free ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "warp",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpb8pr5y0000zcv47rbtixb7"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " below the intended lower edge of the weaving. This becomes the ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "fringe",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmprf5z3f00003wv4kg649pri"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " or knotted finish.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 3: Thread the shed stick through alternate warp ends. Weave 2-3 plain weave rows with scrap yarn at the base of the planned weaving area to space the warp threads evenly and define the starting line.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Weaving the shaped lower section",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "The shape is woven from the bottom upward (as is standard for tapestry). The cartoon's shaped edge is at the bottom; the flat top edge is where you start. On the tapestry loom, the weaving builds upward from the lowest starting point. Begin by weaving the deepest part of a scallop first, then progressively add ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "short rows",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmpstfodo0000w8v4w8h94bzo"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " on either side to build the scallop curve. The outer portions of the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "warp",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmpb8pr5y0000zcv47rbtixb7"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " at the edges of each scallop start weaving later.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 1: Find the lowest point of each scallop on the cartoon. Begin weaving at these three points with your lowest-colour ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "weft",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpb8pr6l0001zcv4yoavpop9"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": ". Each starting point is a section of approximately 10 warp ends.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 2: Weave each section individually. As you build upward, add one or two additional ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "warp",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpb8pr5y0000zcv47rbtixb7"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " ends to each section every few rows, stepping the woven area outward to follow the curve drawn on the cartoon.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 3: When adjacent sections reach the same height (at the top of the scallop curve), merge them into a single continuous ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "weft",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpb8pr6l0001zcv4yoavpop9"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " pass across the full width.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 4: From this merged point, continue weaving the main body of the panel in full-width rows up to the planned 40 cm height.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Warp tension when leaving unwoven areas",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "The ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "warp",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmpb8pr5y0000zcv47rbtixb7"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " ends that are not yet weaving (the ones at the edges of each scallop at the start) sit at their full tension but carry no ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "weft",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmpb8pr6l0001zcv4yoavpop9"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ". This is fine; they will be incorporated as the weaving builds up. Be careful not to accidentally catch these inactive ends when passing the weft through the sections that are already weaving. Use separate bobbins for each active section so the weft does not span the gap between sections.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Finishing the shaped edge",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 1: Remove the panel from the loom. The shaped lower edge will have exposed ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "warp",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpb8pr5y0000zcv47rbtixb7"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " ends of varying lengths.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 2: Working along the shaped lower edge, tie the exposed warp ends in pairs with overhand knots pressed as close as possible to the last woven row. This secures the ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "weft",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpb8pr6l0001zcv4yoavpop9"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " at the edge.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 3: Trim the remaining ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "fringe",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmprf5z3f00003wv4kg649pri"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " to a consistent length following the curve of the shaped edge, or trim each scallop's fringe to a uniform short length just below the knots.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 4 (optional): Add a ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "soumak",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpdw8o9w0000igv4j9xikcl1"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " row along the shaped edge before removing from the loom to give the scallop outline more definition. Work the soumak wraps in a contrasting colour for a decorative finish.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Step 5: Attach a hanging rod or dowel at the top edge through the upper warp loops. The flat top ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "selvedge",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpd4mzcy0000ukv4xwbfevtk"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " should hang straight.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "problem": "The boundary between adjacent scallop sections has a visible gap",
                "solution": "Use the interlocking join technique at the meeting point of each section: loop the two adjacent weft ends around each other at the boundary before turning each one back. This closes the gap without a slit."
              },
              {
                "problem": "The active warp ends are pulling inward at the edges of each section, distorting the warp spacing",
                "solution": "The weft is being pulled too tight at the short-row turns. Arch the weft generously inside the shed before beating, and make sure not to tug the bobbin when turning at the edge of each section."
              },
              {
                "problem": "The shaped outline does not follow the cartoon curve accurately",
                "solution": "The weft-row-step increments are too large. Step the shape by one warp end per row rather than two or three. Smaller steps produce a smoother curve at the cost of a few extra rows."
              }
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
    },
